TXT, CSV, Spreadsheets

Problem 1

In this section, you will learn how to create a simple dataset by hand.

Five kindergarteners participated in a Treasure hunt program, where the goal is to choose the sport that best suits them. Peter’s height is 134 cm and he lives 12.9 km from the Sports Center. Jennifer is 132 cm and lives 3.4 km away, Zoe is 141 cm and lives 21.3 km away, Mary is 138 cm tall and lives 12.1 km away, and Christian is 144 cm tall and lives 65.6 km away. All children were assessed with the Aptitude test and received the following values, respectively: 34, 12, 56, 47, 29. Aptitude tests help psychologists understand the learning ability of a child. Create a dataset that includes the above information. Create XLSX, CSV, TXT and OMV versions of the dataset.

  1. Create a new Excel document treasure_hunt.xlsx in a new project directory kindergarteners.

  2. Enter the data according to the rules you have learned, then save the file. The contents of the Excel file are as shown below. (Be careful with the decimal point, as the image below was created in Hungarian Excel, so a comma was used to indicate the decimal point. In English Excel it is customary to use a period when typing the decimal point.)

  3. In Excel, save the file treasure_hunt.xlsx in CSV (comma separated) file format. It creates the file treasure_hunt.csv. Open this file in the Notepad application.

    As you can see this file above is separated by a tab, the decimal point is a comma because of the Hungarian context. In English, the decimal point is the period. The file looks messy to the human eye, but let’s be clear, it is not intended for human reading, but for machine reading.

  4. In Excel, save the file treasure_hunt.xlsx in TXT (text, TAB separated) format. It creates the file treasure_hunt.txt. Open this file in the Notepad application.

    As you can see, this file above is not comma-separated, it is separated by ten decimal places because of the Hungarian context, and also for this reason the decimal point is a comma. In English, the separator is the comma and the decimal point is the period. The file may look messy to the human eye, but let’s be clear, it is not intended to be read by humans, but by machines.

  5. Start the jamovi application, open the file treasure_hunt.xlsx, then save in jamovi (OMV) format. It creates the file treasure_hunt.omv. You should see the following:

  6. Create a compressed zip file (treasure_hunt.zip) from the XLSX, CSV, TXT and OMV versions of the dataset.

  7. Send the file treasure_hunt.zip to the abari.kurzus@gmail.com. The subject of this email is Lab 04 - Problem 1.

Problem 2

In this section, you will learn how to create a tidy dataset.

The tidy data format has a rectangular shape which means it has columns, rows, and cells, just like in a spreadsheet. However, for rectangular data to be tidy, there are three major principles to adhere to:

  • Each column should hold a single variable
  • Each row should hold a single observation.
  • Each cell should hold a single value (if you follow the first two rules, then each cell should have a single value)

  1. Download the untidy.xlsx and make its tidy equivalent. The dataset uses hypothetical data for four children.

The dataset is untidy because

  • multiple variables are stored in one column: The column sex and age has two variables, obviously sex and age. For example Mike’s value for this column is m_12, meaning that he is a 12 year old male. The sex and age values need to be in different columns.
  • the units are mixed and listed with the observations: For height and weight, we only need the values converted to the same units.
  • variable names are usually in lower case and do not contain spaces, if you want to break them up, use underscores.

  1. Verify that the new database looks as shown in the image. Save the tidy dataset as tidy.xlsx.

  2. Send the file tidy.xlsx to the abari.kurzus@gmail.com. The subject of this email is Lab 04 - Problem 2.

Problem 3

In this section, you will learn how to join datasets.

  1. Download survey_01.xlsx and survey_02.xlsx.

  2. As you can see, the two files contain the imaginary data of 5 children.

    The dataset survey_01.xlsx contains demographic results, while survey_02.xlsx contains test results. The common link is the child ID (id column). Merge the data in the two dataset into a single dataset. Be careful, because 1-1 child is missing from both data tables.

  3. Verify that the new dataset looks as shown in the image. Save the merged dataset as survey.xlsx.

  4. Send the file survey.xlsx to the abari.kurzus@gmail.com. The subject of this email is Lab 04 - Problem 3.
